<img src="/eq/i/icons/Classes/cleric.gif" border=0 alt=""/></a><br>
			


			
			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=clericbalance&message.id=2044#M2044">91</a> of 113
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 474 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV></DIV>
<P>Kytherea, </P>
<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; While you probably get this request ten-bazillion times a day - is it possible to find out how much of the Cleric class list the Devs are contemplating vs what they have thrown out? Knowledge like that, while certainly igniting a flame war, would allow us to know in which direction (if any) the Devs, specifically, and SOE, generally, want to take the Cleric class.&nbsp; For example, why bother saving hard earned LDoN points to buy the Vie spells, if they are only going to be nerfed or superceeded by something new... </P>
<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As with many posters on this board, I too am a little disappointed in SOE for nerfing the Cleric class by providing spells and abilities which are traditionally Clerical to the other classes. Rez is a perfect example of a cleric-only ability. Complete Heal, while possibly a bad idea to introduce into the game on its own merit, should also be a cleric-only ability. </P>
<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; From my first day on Povar, I wanted to be a cleric. They have always been described in roleplaying games as the 'battlefield medics'. These are the characters who feel so strongly in good vs evil that they have gained their deity's favor and the ability to: </P>
<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1) Heal the wounded (Heals and Rezs) <BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2) Protect the good (Buffs) <BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 3) Smite the incarnations of pure evil (DD on Undead and Summoned creatures) </P>
<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sure, I'd like to tank my Cleric. It would be really great! However, if I wanted to do that I'd create a Palladin. In my mind, both Clerics and Palladins are hybrid characters. If you had a 75% Priest, 25% Warrior - you'd have a Cleric. They are tough enough to take hits in battle while still keeping their faith to channel the power of M.Marr (or insert your deity of choice) to keep the party safe and healthy. If you had a 75% Warrior, 25% Priest - you'd have a Palladin. They are tanks, however, they believe so much in their deity that they become the Holy Sword of M.Marr (or insert your deity of choice) smiting all evil everywhere... </P>
<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I would like to think that SOE is bringing the Clerics back to their roots. Perhaps they will create deity specific buffs (you could only buff followers of M.Marr if you are a M.Marr Cleric). Perhaps they will create a leadership skill to allow Clerics to channel the power of their deity to protect the entire party (permanent Vie buff?). Put the role back into roleplaying. </P>
<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Make Clerics the battlefield medic that they should be...... (sorry for the offtopic rant, but I just got going and couldn't stop...) </P>
<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The crux of the question: Ky - can you give us a glimpse of what the Devs have in store for balancing or modifying the Cleric class? Even just a small slice of information would be better than hanging here and thinking that the Devs have abandonned us... </P>
<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Thanks for ANY nuggett of information you can give us.</P>
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
							--<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=539984&resize=true" target="_blank">aarein periander</a><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="http://www.NovusOrsa.org/" target="_novusorsa">Novus Orsa of Povar</a>, Officer and Holy Keeper of the Web
							</div>
								
		</td></tr>
		<tr>
		
